This negative view is however not necessarily coupled with an improved understanding of the process of divorce under Islamic legal principles or an opposition to their underlying spirit – notions defined by Jordanian Muslim scholars as mercy and allowing possibilities for reversion. Islamic views on divorce are broadly discussed alongside main challenges concerning the legal procedure. Women, both in Jordan and abroad, face the hard choice to pay the ‘obligatory’ divorce fee or uncertainly remain in the marriage. The law established in 2008 allows only versatile applications of the ‘obligatory’ fee. A creation of loopholes which questions these in favor, who state that women suffer from unjustifiably exorbitant payments.

Introduction Studies, covering individuals living in the Middle East, demonstrate that the best way of forcing divorce into an accord is to consider the relationship between the concepts of culture, family law and women’s power and standing. As this thesis can show, culture itself is a mutable phenomenon and evolves and changes along with society. It defines law, adapting itself to legal and political decisions. Various laws, different in time and country, govern family issues: one common denominator within family law legislation should be the legal deference on divorce. This legal deference is in Islam the same for both spouses: divorce for those who consider it to be the most viable solution for tension, depression, or sociological reasons could either be initiated by men or women.
